data.enText: to use one cost, payment or situation in order to cancel or reduce the effect of another

data.chText: 为补偿原料成本的增加而提高了价格。
data.enText: Prices have risen in order to offset the increased cost of materials.

data.chText: 什么开支可以获得税项减免？
data.enText: What expenses can you offset against tax ?
used to describe a method of printing in which ink is put onto a metal plate, then onto a rubber surface and only then onto the paper

tr: structure where a wall or building narrows abruptly
a plate makes an inked impression on a rubber-blanketed cylinder, which in turn transfers it to the paper
a horizontal branch from the base of plant that produces new plants from buds at its tips
the time at which something is supposed to begin
example: she knew from the get-go that he was the man for her

tr: cause (printed matter) to transfer or smear onto another surface

example: His skills offset his opponent's superior strength

value.boxr_value: The form offset is used in the present tense and is the past tense and past participle of the verb. offset的过去式和过去分词与原形相同。

value.def: If one thing is offset by another, the effect of the first thing is reduced by the second, so that any advantage or disadvantage is cancelled out.

example.ex: The increase in pay costs was more than offset by higher productivity...
example.tran: 提高的生产率抵消了增加的工资成本后仍有结余。

example.ex: The move is designed to help offset the shortfall in world oil supplies caused by the UN embargo.
example.tran: 此举旨在缓解联合国禁运所造成的世界石油供应短缺的局面。
